    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-12-27T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-12-27T14:00:00-05:00" n="381"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d381">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">501.BB Balkan/12–2547: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Embassy in Yugoslavia</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-12-27T14:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 27, 1947—2 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>797. <gloss target="#t_urtel1">Urtel</gloss> 2367 Dec 25.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d381fn1">Not printed.</note> As follow-up your conversation with
                        Bebler<note n="2" xml:id="d381fn2">Aleš Bebler, Yugoslav Deputy Foreign
                        Minister.</note> concerning Markos’ announcement formation “Free Greek
                    Government” you should find occasion at earliest opportunity in informal <pb
                        facs="0486" n="472" xml:id="pg_472"/> talks with Bebler and/or other
                    appropriate Yugo officials to express view of US Govt that recognition or
                    assistance extended to such self-styled “govt” would be considered flagrant
                    violation principles UN Charter and, in case of Yugo, flouting of <gloss
                        target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> resolution Oct 21. You may also emphasize special
                    responsibilities which Yugo, as member UN, would bear in eyes of world if it
                    should encourage Balkan countries’ recognition of Markos. You may also point out
                    our realization that Communist guerrilla cabinet could not have been announced
                    without tacit approval or active instigation of Cominform as well as Balkan
                    countries which have publicly and consistently expressed hostility to Greece, a
                    UN member in good standing.</p>
                <p>Sent Belgrade; rpt Ankara 725, Athens 2065, Moscow 2068, London 5370, Paris 4606,
                    Rome 2714, Sofia 597, Salonika 165, for Baleom 48, Praha 1413, Warsaw 1109.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lovett</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
